5 (3) Option 2: Certification through a local school district training program. A local
6 school district or group of school districts may seek approval for a training
7 program. The state-approved local school district training program is an alternative
8 to the college teacher preparation program as a means of acquiring teacher
9 certification for a teacher at any grade level. The training program may be offered
10 for all teaching certificates approved by the Education Professional Standards
11 Board, including interdisciplinary early childhood education, except for specific
12 certificates for teachers of exceptional children. To participate in a state-approved
13 local school district alternative training program, the candidate shall possess:
14 (a) A bachelor's degree or a graduate degree;
15 (b) A minimum cumulative grade point average of two and seventy-five
16 hundredths (2.75) on a four (4) point scale or a minimum grade point average
17 of three (3) on a four (4) point scale on the last thirty (30) hours of credit
18 completed, including undergraduate and graduate coursework from a
19 nationally or regionally accredited postsecondary institution; and
20 (c) A passing score on the academic content assessment in the area in which
21 certification is being sought by the applicant as designated by the Education
22 Professional Standards Board. To be eligible to take an academic content
23 assessment, the applicant shall have completed a thirty (30) hour major in the
24 academic content area or five (5) years of experience in the academic content
25 area as approved by the Education Professional Standards Board.
26 An individual may participate in a local school district training program upon
27 meeting the participation requirements as established in this subsection and
